04666nam a22006255i 9780226326559DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263265597 a10.7208/97802263265592doi  a(DE-B1597)523437  a(OCoLC)772845715  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aDT545.84 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a966.680521 aHellweg, Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHunting the Ethical State :bThe Benkadi Movement of Côte d'Ivoire /cJoseph Hellweg. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b15 halftones, 3 maps, 1 line drawing, 2 figures, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tNote on Names, Tense, and Orthography -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Mestizo Dozos: Sacrifice, Shape-Shifting, and the State -- t2. Criminal Instability: History, Identity, and Mimesis in a State of Exception -- t3. Dozos at Home and on the Hunt -- t4. Sacrificing for Security -- t5. Disappearance as Power: Islam and the Secret History of Manimory -- t6. Organizing Benkadi -- t7. Stalking Crime -- t8. The Power in the Nightjar’s Call: Dozo Performance as Social Drama -- t9. Conclusion: From Civic Duty to Civil Unrest -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1990s a nationwide crime wave overtook Côte d’Ivoire. The Ivoirian police failed to control the situation, so a group of poor, politically marginalized, and mostly Muslim men took on the role of the people’s protectors as part of a movement they called Benkadi. These men were dozos—hunters skilled in ritual sacrifice—and they applied their hunting and occult expertise, along with the ethical principles implicit in both forms of knowledge, to the tracking and capturing of thieves. Meanwhile, as Benkadi emerged, so too did the ethnic, regional, and religious divisions that would culminate in Côte d’Ivoire’s 2002–07 rebellion. Hunting the Ethical State reveals how dozos worked beyond these divisions to derive their new roles as enforcers of security from their ritual hunting ethos. Much as they used sorcery to shape-shift and outwit game, they now transformed into unofficial police, and their ritual networks became police bureaucracies. Though these Muslim and northern-descended men would later resist the state, Joseph Hellweg demonstrates how they briefly succeeded at making a place for themselves within it. Ultimately, Hellweg interprets Benkadi as a flawed but ingenious and thoroughly modern attempt by non-state actors to reform an African state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfricanszCôte d'IvoirexRites and ceremonies. 0aAfricanszCôte d'IvoirexRites and ceremonies. 0aCrime preventionzCôte d'IvoirexCitizen participationxHistoryy20th century. 0aCrime preventionzCôte d'IvoirexCitizen participationxHistoryy20th century. 0aHunting customszCôte d'Ivoire. 0aHunting customszCôte d'Ivoire. 0aIslamic occultismxSocial aspectszCôte d'Ivoire. 0aIslamic occultismxSocial aspectszCôte d'Ivoire. 0aSacrificexSocial aspectszCôte d'Ivoire. 0aSacrificexSocial aspectszCôte d'Ivoire. 0aSocial movementszCôte d'IvoirexHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial movementszCôte d'IvoirexHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226326559423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226326559.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA